      section\par
        h1 Working with your Microsoft Account and OneDrive \par
      \par
      section\par
        h2 Working with your Microsoft Account and OneDrive\par
        hr\par
        ul\par
            li Many of the new features in Office 2013 are geared towards saving and sharing files online. \par
            li To use these features, you'll need to get a free Microsoft account (previously called a Windows Live ID) if you don't already have one. \par
            li You can then log in to your Microsoft account to access your OneDrive which is an online storage space for your documents and other files.\par
\par
      section \par
       h2 OneDrive in Microsoft PowerPoint 2013\par
       img(src="images/office basics/account_onedrive.png")\par
\par
      section\par
        h2 Benefits of using a Microsoft Account\par
        ul\par
            li Access your files anywhere: You can save files to your OneDrive, so you'll be able to access them from any computer that has an internet connection. This also helps to keep your files safe if anything happens to your computer.\par
            li Edit documents in your web browser: If you're using a computer that doesn't have Microsoft Office, you can use Office Online (previously known as Office Web Apps) to edit documents in your browser for free. Office Online includes simplified versions of Word, Excel, PowerPoint, and OneNote.\par
            li Share files: It's easy to share your OneDrive files with friends or coworkers. You can choose whether they can edit or just read the files. This option is great for collaboration because multiple people can edit a document at the same time (also known as co-authoring).\par
\par
      section\par
        h2 To sign in to Office 2013:\par
        h3 In the upper-right corner, click Sign in.\par
        img(src="images/office basics/account_sign_in.png")\par
      \par
      section\par
        h2 Type your email address and then click Sign in.\par
        img(src="images/office basics/signin.png")\par
\par
\par
      section\par
        h3 Type your password and then click Sign in.\par
        img(src="images/office basics/password.png")\par
\par
      section\par
        h3 Your account name will now appear in the upper-right corner.\par
        img(src="images/office basics/myaccount.png")\par
        \par
      section\par
        h1 Getting to Know \par
        hr      \par
      \par
      section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')\par
        h2 Opening PowerPoint 2013\par
        ul\par
          li When you open PowerPoint 2013 for the first time, the Start Screen will appear. From here, you'll be able to create a new presentation, choose a template, or access your recently edited presentations.\par
      \par
      section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')\par
        h3 From the Start Screen, locate and select Blank Presentation.\par
        img(src="images/knowing/openklik.png")\par
      \par
      section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')\par
        h3 A new presentation will appear.\par
        img(src="images/knowing/openblank.png")\par
     \par
        \par
      section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')\par
        p PowerPoint 2013 is similar to PowerPoint 2010. If you've previously used PowerPoint 2010, PowerPoint 2013 should feel familiar. But if you are new to PowerPoint or have more experience with older versions, you should first take some time to become familiar with the PowerPoint 2013 interface\par
      \par
      section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')\par
         h3 PowerPoint 2013 Interface\par
         hr\par
         img(src="images/knowing/BACKGROUND_WEB3.png")\par
    \par
      section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')\par
         h2 Working with the PowerPoint environment\par
\par
      section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')\par
         ul\par
           li If you've previously used PowerPoint 2010 or 2007, PowerPoint 2013 will feel familiar.\par
           li It continues to use features like the Ribbon and the Quick Access toolbar, where you will find commands to perform common tasks in PowerPoint, as well as Backstage view.\par
\par
      section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')\par
         h2 The Ribbon\par
         hr\par
         ul\par
           li PowerPoint 2013 uses a tabbed Ribbon system instead of traditional menus.\par
           li The Ribbon contains multiple tabs, each with several groups of commands. You will use these tabs to perform the most common tasks in powerpoint.\par
           img(src="images/knowing/ribbon.png")\par
\par
      section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')\par
         h3 Exploring the Ribbon\par
         hr\par
         p You'll need to move between tabs to perform common tasks in PowerPoint. Knowing where to find the right command will make PowerPoint easier to use.\par
\par
